 Clerks\nJoin March\nCHICAGO, 111. The compre\nhensive organization drive of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor,\nunder direction of William Schoen\nberg, general representative for\nChicago and the Middle West, is\nreported to be meeting with wide\nspread success. The concerted\n\"1 drive has brought many thousands\n1 of workers in many trades under\nthe protective banner of the A. F.\nof L.\nLaundry workers are so far lead\ning the forward march of labor in\nthis city with a sensational gain\n_ of about 18,000 members. Ware\nhouse workers, retail clerks and\ncement workers are among the\nunions that have likewise scored\nnotable gains.\nI sundry Workers Organize 18,000\nThe untiring efforts of President\nSamuel Deal and Business Agent\nCharles Lindgren of the Inside\nLaundry Worker\u2019s Union No. 46,\nin Chicago, has been fruitful to\nthe extent of approximately 18,000\nnewly organized workers in the\nlaundries.\nThese workers have been under\npaid these many years and were\nin need of an organization that will\nbring better wages and shorter\nhours of work and all of the other\nfavorable conditions that only con\ncerted action through a union can\nsupply. The credit of this success\nful organization work is due to\nseveral years of untiring effort on\nthe part of Mr. Deal and Mr. Lind\ngren.\nWarehouse Workers Gain 1,300\nThe warehouse workers in Chi\ncago have been organized to the\nextent of 1,300 new members un\n-1 der the banner of the American\nFederation of Labor. This field is\nbeing covered by Organizer Joseph\nBriegel. 666 Lake Shore Drive, the\noffice of the Chicago branch of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nRetail Clerks Increase Strength;\nGain C. I. O. Group\nThe Retail Clerks International\nProtective Association in Chicago\nhas made, and is still making a\nstrenuous drive for new members.\nAmong some of their activities\nare the following newly organized\nlocals: Local No. 1248 with a mem\nbership of 1,600; Local No. 1355\nwith 400 members; Local No. 1397\nwith 120 members, and Local No.\n963 with a large membership; the\nlast group were C. I. 0., but now\nare bona fide members of the Re\ntail Clerks International Associa\ntion and affiliated with the Ameri\ncan Federation of Labor.\n20,000 Cement Workers Organized\nThe cement industry throughout\nthe entire United States is being\nrapidly organized under the direct\nsupervision of General Representa\ntive William Schoenberg of the\nChicago A. F. of L. office.\nThis difficult field of organiza\ntion is being successfully accomp\nlished by Mr. Schoenberg and his\nimmediate organizers. In order\nto keep up with the activities of\nthe organization work in this field,\nMr. Schoenberg has placed on the\nwall of his office a map of the\nUnited States and every cement\nplant in the country is marked\nthereon. When a plant is organ\nized under the A. F. of L. a red\nmarker is placed on that spot.\nThere are a good many red mark 7\nera on the map.\nThere are approximately 20,000\ncement workers now organized and\naffiliated with the American Fed\neration of Labor.\nMIAMI INDUSTRIAL BANK\nKEEPS HOURS OF 9 TO 4\nBelieving there are many per\nsons who cannot transact their\nbusiness during ordinary banking\nhours, including workingmen and\nwomen, the Miami Industrial\nBank, at 46 W. Flagler street, has\nestablished for its business hours\nthe period from 9 a. m. to 4 p. m.\nOfficers of the company are R.\nDeWitt King, chairman of the\nboard; John M. Ogden, president;\nJ. T. Owens, vice president and\ncomptroller; Roy A. Perry, secre\ntary.\nElsewhere in this newspaper ap\npears a statement showing the ex\ncellent condition of the bank,\nwhich is a member of the Federal\nReserve Corporation, under which\ndeposits are guaranteed up to\n*6,000.\nThe largest codfish on record\n211 pounds and more than six feet\nlong\u2014 -was caught on a line trawl\noff Massachusetts in 1895.\nMUSICIANS\u2019\nNOTES\nThe strolling detriment \u2014A fa\nmily reunion under one roof \u2014Hill-\nbillies to the dogs\u2014Store opening\n-Secretary newly groomed\u2014Re\nhearsals in the club room\u2014Butter\nand egg contracting\u2014no parking.\nBob Nolan, with a 10-piece local\nband, opened this week at the\n\"International Club\" on Miami\nBeach. One more score for the\nlocal units.\nBen Johnson, from Providence,\nR. 1., an ex-member of this local,\nreturns with four others as a tra\nveling unit to supply the music at\nWhitman Hotel.\nCarl Carlson, brother to Presi\ndent Arthur Carlson, is in town\nto play the Whitman engagement.\nCarl was violin concertmaster in\nthe long-gone Olympic theatre or\nchestra when 30 men played in the\npit under Emanuel Baer. Carl is\none of the family reunion-ites re\nferred to in the first paragraph.\nJoe Weinstock imported five mu\nsicians to play at Minsky\u2019s Music\nHall. The executive board\u2019s pre\nrogative was exercised to the de\ngree of sending three of the group\nback to New York. At present\nthe engagement consists of two\ncut-of-towners and six local men.\nThe electric organ is not the\nleading displacer of musicians. The\nrecord seems to be Weld by the\nsmall strolling units of guitars,\naccordians and the like. The hole\nthese outfits are digging into the\nemployment possibilities is getting\nbigger and bigger. We should al\nways remember that the member\nship of this local runs some over\n400 and everything possible should\nbe done to get these people work\ning.\nThe local officers are untiring in\ntheir efforts to make all engage\nments local engagements. To do\nthis against the traveling band\nstrongholds is just more headaches\nadded to the ones they already\nhave.\nJohnny Sbraccia, at Hialeah\nrace track, comes in fourth on the\nsaxaphone. Here is an instance\nwhere it is necessary to make a\n\u201cshow\u201d in order to have a \u201cplace.\u201d\nWhy does the Royal Palm Club\nresort to a show and band from\nLos Angeles at the expense of the\njobs of a good local band?\nThe Biscayne dog track will em\nploy a hillbilly unit for two weeks,\nafter which they wil try a Ha\nwaiian outfit. There is no truth\nto the statement that the dogs will\nrun faster away from this music\nthan any other kind.\nCoffee and sandwiches available\ndown stairs in the newly opened\ncorner store. As this place is of\nadvantage to the Local it deserves\nthe patronage of all members.\nThe duck pin record this week\nwas 126 and Dave Frank got the\npieces of eight bits while a like\nminiature treasure went to Jerry\nClark for his high of 212 at ten\npins.\nEddie Latzke is reported to be\nplaying with the band at Bayfront\nPark and we hope the report is\ntrue.\nIs it Minsky\u2019s Cusic or Cusic\u2019s\nMinsky\nThe international executive\nboard is at the Everglades hotel\nand this local gives them the usual\nbig welcome to tour midst.\nTime out until next week.\nWOMAN'S UNION LABEL\nLEAGUE PLANS PARTIES\n\nInauguration on Thursday, Jan\nuary 13, by the Woman\u2019s Union\nLabel League of the plan of meet\ning every Thursday afternoon at\n1:30 o\u2019clock in their new quarters\nin the Carpenters\u2019 building, 47 N.\nW. Third street, was marked by a\ngood attendance and an interesting\nsession. One new member was\nreceived.\nStarting with Thursday, Janu- i\nary 20, it is planned to hold a card\nparty every two weeks at the\nquarters, alternating with the reg\nular meetings.\nMRS. E. C. STONE,\nReporter.\nSOCIAL SECURITY TAXES\nREQUIRED FROM BARBERS\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014The re\nported widespread attempt of some\nof the nation\u2019s master barbers to\navoid liability for payment of so\ncial security taxes is believed to\nhave been effectively curbed.\nThe Internal Revenue Bureau\nruled that barbers under contract\nwith a barber shop which requires\nthem to conform to certain shop\nrules and who receive for their\nservices a percentage of the\nmoney taken in by them, are em\nployes of the shop and therefore\nsubject to the usual social secur\nity taxes.\nMIAMI CITIZEN, JANUARY 20,1938\n570,000 WORKERS LOST\nJOBS DURING NOVEMBER\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014Although\nemployment dropped 570,000 dur\ning November, the greatest reduc\ntion in industrial employment for\nany November since 1920, accord\ning to a recent announcement by\nSecretary of Labor Frances Per\nkins, the total employed persons\nwas about the same as for the\nsame period of the previous year.\nAlso, while pay roll totals dropped\n$25,900,000 from October to No\nvember, statistics of the Labor de\npartment show pay rolls were still\n$11,000,000 higher than in 1936.\nMiss Perkins maintained that\nthe current business recession is\n\u201cpurely economic\u2019\u2019 and a \"regular\nadjustment in a period of recov\nery,\u201d with no one person, group or\nthing in particular to blame. \"This\nis a natural thing,\u201d the statement\nsaid. \u201cIt has occurred before in\nrecovery movements.\u201d\nDeclines in factory employment\nin 81 industries have been wide\nspread, with increases of 11.4 per\ncent in the silverware and plated\nware industry, 18 per cent in the\naluminum industry, and smaller\nincreases in eight other industries.\nNon-manufacturing industries, with\none exception, showed declines, for\na grand average drop of 5.8 per\ncent in employment since October.\nWhile the secretary declined to\npredict when the recession would\nend, she stated retail trade had\nnot declined as much as manufac\nturers\u2019 sale, with the result that\ntoo-large inventories are being\nremoved and with them removal\nof the cause of unemployment.\nThe kettledrum is the only kind\nof drum having a definite musical\npitch. It may be tuned to any one\nof the notes within its compass\nof half an octave.\nDubinsky Calls C. I. O.\nResponsible for Failure\n(Continued from Page One)\nas expressed by Mr. Lewis that the\nA. F. of L. admit all C. I. O.\nunions without any conditions or\npreliminary understanding.\n\u201cSuch a peace would be a patch\nwork peace and would mean con\ntinuing the fight in the A. F. of\nL.,\u201d Mr. Dubinsky declared. \"This\nis not the way to unity.\u201d\nAt the same time, however, Mr.\nDubinsky announced that although\nwe have not been consulted and\nhave had no say as to its adminis\ntration and policies,\u201d the Interna\ntional Ladies Garment Workers\nUnion would not withdraw from\nthe C. I. O. but would continue to\npress for peace.\n\"We do not believe that our\nwithdrawal from the C. I. O. bene-\nBUDWEISER\nKing of Bottled Beer\n\nBALLANTINE'S\n100 1 BEER 4 ALE\nUNION Purity Body Flavor\nMADE RUPPERT'S BEER\nBalanced Flavor\n\nRHEINGOLD\nNo fancy Claims \u2014Just GOOD Beer\nb\nJ GENUINE\nCHEVROLET\nS SERVICE\n^^^CHEVROLET-TRAINED\nMechanics\nCHEVROLET-DESIGNED\nF BL Tools\nGENUINE CHEVROLET\nParts\nV save money-protect\nm YOUR CAR INVESTMENT\nSOUTHLAND MOTOBS INC\nUsed Car Dent 1320-22 N. E. 2od Ave.\nfit the cause of unity and peace,\u201d\nhe said. \"We do not believe that\nwithdrawal of any one union either\nfrom the A. F. of L or C. I. O.\nwould promote the cause of peace.\nBut it is our definite conviction\nthat peace will ultimately have to\nbe established in the labor move\nfment. We want to make our con\ntribution to such a solution, confi\ndent that history will appreciate\nand justify our contribution.\u201d\nWith' the statement that the A.\nF. of L., through its negotiating\ncommittee of three, had met sub\nstantially the vital demands of the\nC. I. 0., Mr. Dubinsky warned that\n\u201cthe grave crisis of the labor\nmovement, accentuated by the\nbusiness recession and the growth\nof unemployment,\u201d required that\nthe faftional war in organized la\nbor be speedily ended.\nUrges C. I. O. to Stop Raids\nHe warned also that \"the C. I.\nO. has passed its honeymoon per\niod\u201d and that further advance by\norganized labor under the Wagner\nact was possible only through\npeace in the labor movement. As\na first move toward resumption-of\npeace negotiations Mr. Dubinsky\npleaded that the C. I. O.\"stop raid\nraiding and dividing existing\nunions of the A. F. of L. and con\nfine itself to organizing of the un\norganized.\u201d\nDirecting some of his sharpest\ndarts at the Communists and their\npress, who have accused the Inter\nnational Ladies Garment Workers\nUnion of misrepresenting the facts\nof the situation affecting the fac\ntional labor conflict, Mr. Dubinsky\nsaid:\n\u201cWe have not forgotten the de\nstructive role of the Communists\nin the past, but more recently, we\nhave been told, they have adopted\na new line. The new line seems\nto be the old line. The Commun\nists and their official organs have\nbeen among those who have ven\ntured to criticize us for our posi\ntion. They have charged us with\nbetraying the labor movement.\nSince when has expression of opin\nion, an honest revaluation of facts,\nconstituted a betrayal of the labor\nmovement\n\u201cThe Communists speak much of\nthe rank and file. The rank and\nfile, they say, should have the say.\nI claim to be a real representative\nof the rank and file, which appar\nently has no say in the C. I. O.\ncouncils, where I have been a min\nority of one. Well, I am used to\nthat. I was a minority of one in\nthe executive council of the Ameri\ncan Federation of Labor before I\nresigned.\n\u201cThe position I defend is the\nposition of my union, as expressed\nat its convention in Atlantic City\nlast summer. The resolution adopt\ned by that convention provided for\nour continued affiliation with the\nC. I. O. and support of its cam\npaigns, while continuing to work\nconsistently for peace with the\nA. F. of L., an honest peace, on\nthe basis of recognition of indus\ntrial unionism, and vested our gen\neral executive board with full\npower to act in any emergency for\nthe protection of the interests of\nour members.\u201d\nWith respect to the claim that\nthe C. I. O. had 4,000,000 members\nand that all these should be ad\nmitted into the A. F. of L. without\nprevious conditions or understand\ning, Mr. Dubinsky declared that\ncareful analysis had disclosed that\nthe ten or twelve original C. I. O.\nunions represent 75 per cent of the\nmembership of the C. I. O.\n\"I have never been for peace at\nany price,\u201d Mr. Dubinsky declared,\nreferring to a statement by Mr.\nLewis objecting to peace on such\nterms. \"Nor have our members or\ngeneral executive board been for\npeace at any price, but what we\nsay is that when there is a chance\nto make an honorable peace, let\nus have it.\u201d\nIn pleading for a resumption of\nARNOLD'S\nBARBER SHOP\n(Union Shop)\n1 BARBERS IN ATTENDANCE\n606 S. W. Twelfth Avenue i\nMcAllister Florist\nFLOWERS\nFor All Occasions\n\u2019Phone 2-5778\n647 WEST tXAGLER ST.\n27 1301\nn. w. a Wesi\nFifth Flagler\nBtrcet TWQ SUpER FOOD STORES\nUSE ONLY\nThe BEST in PAINTS and VARNISHES\nPhone Call Will Bring Our Bepreeontetive\nHOPKINS-CARTER HARDWARE CO.\nPhone 2-5194 135-139 South Miami Avenue, Miami, Florida\nHeadquarters for the well-known union-made\nW. L. DOUGLAS Shoes for men and women\nECONOMY SHOE STORE\n10 N. E. First Street' WKflr\nW. L. PHILBRICK\nFUNERAL DIRECTOR\nSERVING GREATER MIAMI\n660 W. Flagler Phone 2-4131\nFLAGLER CHEVROLET CO., INC.\nSALES SERVICE\nPhone 2-4118\nUsed Car 2-6769\n1051-1065 WEST FLAGLER STREET\nRAILEY-MILAM INC\nHARDWARE\nHouseware Tools Paints\n27-39 W. Flagler St Pllftne 3-2146\nH .a-^ib.*\nil&t mHhH K. &>^Hh\nSQ IPISiBR uj g sol\nAA^^W\nw llll ^W at\u00df Wr^ s M\nK tuwaW IWW^9\nWSS\nB bsmvfw- IV\u00bb;;<^9\nHI w l u> _\npeace negotiations. Mr. Dubinsky\npointed out that \"labor has already\nsuffered a series of defeats\u201d as a\nresult of the split in its ranks and\ncited the defeat of the Wag ne i\nWages and Hours bill at the last\nsession of congress as an example\n\"That defeat would never have\ntaken place if labor had been\nunited.\u201d he said. The welfare oi\nthe entire trade union movement is\ndefinitely and deeply affected by\nthis situation.\u201d\nr H\nSpreads Farther* Lasts Longer* Look Bdlvr\nSHKItWIII-WILLIMn\nF